Exercise classification using Athos EMG-sensor garments¶

The ability to quantify an individual's level of physical activity is a major challenge in personal health and fitness. Although heart rate monitors and step counters have existed for decades, devices and data systems for measuring how well an athlete's muscles and joints function are still needed.

ATHOS is making a significant step towards filling this need, by providing smart garments with embedded EMG (electromyography) sensors for the upper and lower extremity. These sensors measure muscle activity in real time during physical exercise, enabling quantification of biomechanical metrics such as intensity, cadence, and timing.

In this blog post I collaborate with ATHOS to investigate the question:

Can muscle activity data from Athos EMG sensors help keep track of what exercises a user is performing during his or her workouts?

If so, Athos technology could potentially eliminate the need for users to manually log their own workouts--opening the door to a wide range of services including exercise-specific workout statistics and personalized training recommendations.

To tackle this question, I'll be working with an anonymized dataset collected by ATHOS in their laboratory. This dataset contains over 2,000 trials from more than 50 different exercises performed by ~70 people. Each trial comprises streams of continuous EMG sensor data from eight different leg muscles. To figure out how signals from these sensors correspond to individual physical exercises, I'll be applying some machine learning techniques in Python that I've been learning here at Insight Data Science.

  • First, I'll clean up the raw data and parse out any useful meta-data from file names, folder names, and README contents.
  • Then, I'll do some exploratory analysis to identify quantitative features that could be used to explain differences in muscle activity between exercises.
  • Finally, I'll develop and test some models for classifying exercises, and tune their parameters to optimize performance.

This post serves to document the steps I took in my analysis, and is intended for a somewhat technical reader--ideally, someone at Athos who needs to work with this data. High-level function calls and some example code is included in this post and can be shown/hidden by clicking the link at the top of this page.

Data preparation¶

Usually, the first step in executing a data science project is data preparation, or "cleaning". This process might involve reorganization or reformatting of data files, identification and filtering of 'bad' data, and handling of special cases.

The data I received from Athos was not unlike the kind of data one might find in a typical biomechanics lab. Upon initial inspection it appeared to have been collected, organized, and annotated manually, so I knew I'd have to do a significant amount of pre-processing before embarking on analysis.

My workflow consisted of the following steps:

  • parse out labels (person, exercise, leg side, other...) from data folders and CSV files
  • inspect some of the data to see what we're working with
  • identify experiment files with potentially corrupt data
  • summarize the dataset
  • select portions of the data for training/testing/validation

My understanding is that Athos has since transitioned to a more streamlined data collection and processing pipeline. However, their older data is incredibly valuable, so they asked for my help extracting insights from it.

Parsing¶

Data was in the form of CSV files nested under various parent directories corresponding to the type of exercise performed and the person performing the exercise. As is often the case, the directory and folders were named using different conventions, sometimes with misspellings. So my first challenge was to parse out the relevant metadata from file and folder names and generate appropriate labels.

To achieve this, I used a combination of regular expressions and fuzzy string matching to:
1) capture the relevant tokens within folder and file names, and
2) map those tokens to a set of known exercises and individuals, which serve as labels for the data.

Here's an example of how parsing of CSV file names using regular expressions might work for a few cases, where the captured tokens correspond to Person, Exercise, Leg_side, Weight_lifted, and Additional_info:

In [4]: 
# EXAMPLE:  parse labels from csv file names
for s in ['MarkSena_BBSquat45.csv             ',
          'MarkSena_ProneHamstringCurlR30_2_.csv',
          'MarkSena _ButtBlaster_L20plus45.csv']:

    labels = re.findall(r"^([a-zA-Z ]+)(?:_| _)([A-Za-z]+)_?([LR])(\d*)(.{0,4})\.csv", s)
    if not labels: labels = re.findall(r"^([a-zA-Z ]+)(?:_| _)([A-Za-z]+)_?([LR])?(\d*)(.{0,8})\.csv", s)
        
    print s, '\t-> ', labels

MarkSena_BBSquat45.csv              	->  [('MarkSena', 'BBSquat', '', '45', '')]
MarkSena_ProneHamstringCurlR30_2_.csv 	->  [('MarkSena', 'ProneHamstringCurl', 'R', '30', '_2_')]
MarkSena _ButtBlaster_L20plus45.csv 	->  [('MarkSena ', 'ButtBlaster', 'L', '20', 'plus45')]

Inspection¶

At the early stages of analysis, nothing beats visually inspecting the data to get a feel for its properites. In the case of ATHOS' data, I knew that I would be working with times series data from eight EMG sensors taking muscle-activity readings from the inner and outer quads, hamstrings, and glutes.

To inspect the EMG data, I created plots of the muscle activity for the left and right legs during all of the represented exercises and dumped them to a folder to thumb through.

Here's an example of stair climbing. As one would expect, the muscle contractions alternate between legs.

Cleaning¶

After getting a feel for the data in general, it's a great idea to come up with some simple quality metrics and plot their distributions. This can help identify any obvious issues or errors (i.e. "data smells") that could potentially affect downstream results. In my case, after inspecting the data, not only did I observe some patterns in the data, but I also found some evidence of bad EMG recordings.

Based on some of my observations, I came up with some criteria for discerning 'good' data from potentially 'bad' data, and excluded a portion of the data. Notably, most of the data files I excluded had a large fraction of 0-values for one or more of the EMG leads, which could have been due to a broken lead, or bad contact between the sensor and the user's skin. Other quality metrics I evaluated include:

  • number of rows - to find files that are too short or long enough to sample multiple times
  • max value across all channels (below 30,000) - magnitude of the signal
  • median value across all channels - find files with signals that are too low
  • number of spikes to 65535 - files where sensor was freaking out
  • max fraction of zero values across channels - possibly dead sensors?
  • max fraction of consecutive non-zero values - files with temporal binning issues
In [10]: 
# calculate quality metrics like the fraction of 0-value
files_qc = my.check_quality(files)
files_qc.to_csv('../data/files_qc.csv')

Based on this, we can define some exclusion criteria:

  • trials must be longer than 500, or ~12.5 sec (not too short)
  • the fraction of repeated values must be less than 60% (not too laggy)
  • the fraction of zero values must be less than 30% (no dead sensors)
  • the median signal value must be less than 100 (not too noisy)

and then apply these criteria to remove "bad" files.

In [20]: 
files_precleaned = files.copy() # keep a copy of the uncleaned files to analyze later
files = my.exclude_by_quality(files, files_qc, '../data/dirty/')

excluded 570 files of 2415

Exploratory analysis¶

After cleaning the data and inspecting it to get a feel for its properties, one can start to do some exploratory data analysis. This might involve applying transformations to the data, designing features that characterize different aspects of the data, understanding the relationships among those features, and possibly transforming those features or selecting subsets of them to reduce the dimensionality of the feature space.

Feature engineering was a critical component of my project. I knew that I'd have to design some features that:

  • summarize arbitrarily long chuncks of sensor data
  • are diverse enough to characterize independent aspects of an exercise
  • are intuitive and biomechanically relevant

As a start, I designed sets of features that "live" in the EMG-signal domain, the frequency domain, and the time domain.

  • The first set (8 features) represent the intensity of muscle contraction for the inner and outer quads, hamstrings, and glutes for the right and left legs.
    Intensities were quantified as the mean peak values for each sensor channel.
  • The next set (2 features) represent the cadence, or tempo of muscle contraction during the exercise.
    Cadence was quantified by extracting the two strongest frequency components across all sensor channels.
  • The last set (8 features) represent relative timing of muscle contraction.
    Relative timing was quantified as phase lag (derived from the cross-correlation) between pairs of sensor channels.

Here's a nice scatter plot to visualize the relationships between features. The diagonals show a kernel-density estimation plot for each feature.

In [37]: 
# visualize features in the training or test set
ax = viz.plot_feature_scatter(feat_train, files_train,
                             write_dst='../data/results/figs/features_scatter.pdf')

There are some pretty distinct correlations between the inner (VM) and outer (VL) quad muscles of the same leg, as might be expected. Some natural clustering is also apparent in the plots of exercise frequency (f1 and f2) versus phase shift (p_*), most notably, for the inner and outer quad muscles.

Model development and testing¶

Now that we have a reduced set of Exercise labels, clean data, and reasonable features, we can train a few classifiers to distinguish between different exercises.

In [97]: 
X_train = feat_train
y_train = files_train.Exercise

X_test = feat_test
y_test = files_test.Exercise
In [109]: 
y_train = y_train.replace(to_replace='Prone Hamstring Curl', value='Hamstr. Curl'); # shorten for asthetics
y_test = y_test.replace(to_replace='Prone Hamstring Curl', value='Hamstr. Curl'); # shorten for asthetics

First, let's try an SVM with a Gaussian kernel. SVMs are binary classifiers by definition, but they can be used in a "one-vs-rest" (or in the case of scikit-learn, "one-vs-one") framework to act as a multi-class classifier.

In [110]: 
from sklearn import svm
In [149]: 
svc = svm.SVC(gamma=0.001, C=100.)
svc.fit(X_train, y_train)

my.prediction_report(svc.predict(X_test), y_test, svc.classes_)

  Leg Press       0.75      0.79      0.77       116
     Stairs       0.89      0.92      0.90        62

avg / total       0.81      0.81      0.81       349
Out[149]:
81.375358166189116

Wow, that worked pretty well. When I first got this result I was pleasantly surprised.

But by looking horizontally along rows, it's clear that this classifier is confusing instances of Butt Blaster with Leg Press, and Glute Bridge with Hamstring Curl. As we showed earlier, in this particlar dataset, Leg Press is over-represented while Glute Bridge was under-represented, so this result makes sense. If trained on unbalanced labels, a classifier will more often predict the classes that are over-represented.

To account for unbalanced classes, we can apply some sort of weighting scheme. This is easy to do in scikit-learn using the class_weights parameter, which scales the each class's C-parameter by the inverse frequency of that class.

In [113]: 
# class_weight='auto' accounts for unbalanced classes
svc = svm.SVC(gamma=0.001, C=100., class_weight='auto')
svc.fit(X_train, y_train)

my.prediction_report(svc.predict(X_test), y_test, svc.classes_);


percent correct: 76.5042979943
             precision    recall  f1-score   support

Butt Blaster       0.64      0.87      0.73        75
Glute Bridge       0.41      0.78      0.54        18
Hamstr. Curl       0.89      0.97      0.93        78
  Leg Press       0.84      0.47      0.60       116
     Stairs       0.91      0.94      0.92        62

avg / total       0.80      0.77      0.76       349

By accounting for unbalanced classes, the overall accuracy was not better, but that's OK. Since we don't expect Leg Press (which is over-represented in this dataset) to be performed more often under normal circumstances we shouldn't "cheat" by predicting it more often than we should.

Optimizing model performance¶

Great, we've got a model that does a fairly good job of predicting the kind of activity an individual is doing. Now we can try to optimize model performance on the training data using a grid search with a nested 5-fold cross validation. During this process, models are trained on 4/5ths of the training data and evaluated on 1/5th (this is repeated 5 times). Parameters are then chosen based on the average of some performance metric (in our case, 'recall').

This technique is nice because it leaves our test set untouched (which is critical), without requiring us to set aside a separate set of data strictly for parameter tuning.

In [135]: 
# following grid search example on sklearn
from sklearn.cross_validation import train_test_split
from sklearn.grid_search import GridSearchCV

tuned_parameters = [{'kernel': ['rbf'], 'gamma': [1, 1e-1, 1e-2, 1e-3], 'class_weight': ['auto'], 'C': [1, 10, 100, 1000, 10000]}]
score = 'recall'

print("# Tuning hyper-parameters for %s" % score)
print

grid = GridSearchCV(svm.SVC(C=1, cache_size=500), tuned_parameters, cv=5, scoring=score, n_jobs=-1)
grid.fit(X_train, y_train)

We can use a similar approach to tune the parameters of an Extremely Randomized Trees classifier. Here we'll use a random search instead of a grid search...just for the sake of randomness, of course ;-)

In [138]:

One nice aspect of Tree Ensembles like Random Forests and Extra Trees is that (at least in scikit-learn) it's straightforward to compute feature importances. The basic idea is to scramble each feature column and then measure the decrease in model performance.

Apparently, (see stackoverflow) these are calulated using "Gini importance" or "mean decrease impurity", which I imagine is similar to "mean decrease accuracy", but the measure of interest is Precision rather than Recall.

In [146]: 
importance = random_search.best_estimator_.feature_importances_
ix = importance.argsort()
index = feat_test.columns.values
df_importance = pandas.DataFrame({'feature importance':importance}, index=index).sort(['feature importance'], ascending=False)
df_importance.plot(kind='bar', figsize=(12, 6));

We could have also done something similar for our SVM using Recursive Feature Elimination

Next steps and future work¶

OK, in this post we've gone through the whole pipeline of a prototypical data science project, from data cleaning to validation of a predictive model--but there's always more work to be done! Below are some further questions and potential areas of improvement.

  • Did cleaning the data improve the results? How do we automate or fix this for future datasets?
  • Could accelerometer data improve activity classification? By how much?
  • How can activity classification benefit users? What other DataSci techniques could provide value?
  • How much does prediction accuracy go down with an increasing number of activties (which also have less exemplars).
  • Should unilateral exercises performed by the Left and Right legs be classified separately?
  • Can one use a hierchical clustering method to identify groups of similar exercises, and make predictions within those known (or assumed) clusters?
  • Can predictions be made based on time-series data (e.g. using a Hidden Markolf Model or Recurrent Neural Net) instead of based on 10-second time intervals?
  • To what extent dos the length of time windows affect prediction accuracy?
